Kim Jong Il Sends Wreath to Bier of Ri Dan 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 5 (KCNA) -- Leader Kim Jong Il on Jan. 4 sent a wreath to the bier of Ri Dan, People's Actor of the State Theatrical Company who is deputy to the DPRK Supreme People's Assembly and winner of Kim Il Sung Order, expressing deep condolences over his death.
 Ri died of myocardial infarction on Jan. 3, Juche 93 (2004) at the age of 85. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 He worked hard for the development of the Juche-oriented dramatic art for many years and greatly contributed to bringing about a signal turn in dramas by successfully directing the revolutionary dramas "A Mountain Shrine," "Blood at an International Conference" and "A Letter from a Daughter." &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The Presidium of the DPRK SPA and the Central Committee of the General Federation of the Unions of Literature and the Arts of Korea on Jan. 3 published a joint obituary of Ri Dan.

Korean People's Cause Supported 
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 5 (KCNA) -- A meeting was held on the subject of "Let's unite against imperialism" in Kolkata, India, on December 25 last year on the occasion of the "day of international solidarity in the anti-imperialist struggle."
 Debabrata Biswas, general secretary of the C.C., the All-India Forward Bloc, in his report underscored the need to achieve the firm unity of the anti-imperialist forces to cope with the evermore undisguised arbitrary practices of the U.S. in recent years. He said that his party, a signatory to the Pyongyang Declaration, would positively support the struggle to revive socialism and the just struggle of the Korean people for the country's reunification. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 A Kolkata declaration was adopted at the meeting. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The declaration noted that the most important task before the world people struggling for peace and democracy is to achieve the firm unity of the working class and further intensify the struggle against imperialism. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Congratulating the DPRK, Cuba and other countries on their successes made in the protracted struggle against imperialism, the declaration called for lifting worldwide voice "Let's unite against imperialism."

U.S. Urged to Properly Approach Six-way Talks
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pyongyang, January 5 (KCNA) -- The six-way talks may be resumed at an early date or may be delayed or scuttled depending on how preparations are made for their resumption, says Rodong Sinmun today in a signed commentary.
 Referring to the fact that the DPRK has exerted positive efforts for the resumption of the talks, the commentary goes on: &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. improper stand and attitude toward the resumption of the talks can not but pose a very serious problem. The U.S. is pressurizing the DPRK to scrap its nuclear weapons program first while shelving the issue of making a switchover in its policy toward the DPRK. This is a revelation of the U.S. true intention not to put an end to the hostile and belligerent bilateral relations and co-exist with the DPRK in peace. It also discloses the U.S. true intention to disarm the DPRK in an irreversible and verifiable manner and destroy it. It is a brigandish true purpose sought by the U.S. to completely disarm the DPRK and destroy it by the tactics of throttling it to the last. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 The U.S. insistence on such stand would only destroy foundation of dialogue. It was attributable to the U.S. improper attitude and stand that talks and negotiations ended without any success in the past after undergoing turns and twists. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 What matters here is where to focus attention in making preparations for the resumption of the talks. The preparations should be orientated toward reaching an agreement on actions at the first phase along with "words-for-words" commitments. The actions to be taken at the first phase are for the U.S. and the neighbouring countries to take measures in return for the DPRK's complete freeze of its nuclear activities. This is a starting point and a core issue of furthering the process of talks. &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;
 Clear and responsible is what the U.S. should do for the resumption of the six-way talks. Whether the six-way talks are resumed or not entirely depends on how the U.S. makes preparations for them. A ball is in the U.S. court.

